{"/service/ndnp/lu/batch_lu_iceman_ver01/data/sn88064069/00211100965/1921012701/0027.xml":{"full_text":"THE BIENVILLE DEMOCRAT\nOfficial Journal Bienville Parish and Town of lrcadia, L.ouisiana\nS. A. COOK,. ....................Editor and Propreitor\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY\n$2.00 A YEAR IN BIENVILLE PARISH-$2.25 A YEAR OUTSIDE THE\nPARISH\nADVERTISING RATES ON APPLICATION\nEntered-as Second Class Matter, April 11, 1912 at the postoffice I\nin Arcadia, La., under the Act of March 3, I879.\nProsperity Ahead\nThere is much comfort to be had\nfrom the statement recently of Judge\nElbert H. Gary, head of the United\nStates Steel Corporation, the greatest I\nbusiness concern the world has ever\nproduced.\nJudge .(:!ry says a long period of\nwonderful prosperity is just ahead ol\nthe people of the United States.\nWhen Judge Gary opens his mouth\nhe is in the habit of saying some\nthing, and he never says a thing un\nless he knows what he is talking\nabout.\nHe has been a wise prophet in the\npast, because he possesses the ability\nto read conditions and possibilities as\nthey are.\nThere is no reason why his prophesy\nshould not be one of wisdom in thh\ncase, because there no reason why we\n.should not prosper and every reason\nwhy we should.\nBanks and financiers gederally stat\nthat we have passed through our wors\nperiod of depression and are now oi\nthe up grade. Only the rankest kind\nof pessimism can hold us back.\nAnd who wants to be a pessimist\nwhen every human instnict spurs us\noi to optimism?\nLet's demonstrate our faith in the\nreturn of prosperity by recognizing the\nfact that it is here and by doing our\nshare toward its maintenance in thi:\ncommunity.\nLet the watchword be production\nwisdom in spending, and the employ\nmeet of a systematic course of say\nfag.\nA proportionate amount of the pros\nperlty of the country belongs to th\npeople of this conimunity.\nLet's get all we can and keep a'\nWe get.\nOther communities will 1b doing th'\nJaw\nCHARTER\nef the Arealla Meter Comaql Inc.\nState ot Louisiana:\nParish of Blenville.\nThis day before e, OCarl Goff a\npotary public Within ,and for safd\nParish and; State, duly- comissioned\nAd saworn, and in the prgenoeof\nthe witnesses whose names are here\nunto subserlbed, personally Came ant\nand appeared, R. Brnest Smith, Jas.\nRoberts and Joseph Winkler, sub.\nscribing hereunto as incorporators,\nall over the age of majority, whose\nresidences are as follows:\nB. rnest Smith, Minden, in Web\nater Parish, Louisiana.\nJ. C. Roberts, Shreveport, in, Cad\ndo Parish, Louisiana.\n'Joseph Winkler, Arcadia, in Bien.\n'ViIe Parish, Loulaana, who several\nly declared:\nThat availing thenmweree of the\nprmvisimon of the laws of the State\nof Louisiana relative to the organisa\ntie of eabrporation, and especially of\n4e,\u007f No,'. of the Genral Assembly\n.of I mdAthey do hereby organise them\n.ielo~ weu as suchb other per~,n\n..'as may heaefter bei emoiated with\nothem, into. a corpratlon under th\ntollowing provislonQ to-wit:\n(a) the name of this corporation\n.hall be th u Area lr Moe I, Ine\n(b) th\u007fobect, -ni l\u007fpa\u007fe:o thl.\ncorporation shall be to buy shd an l\nbaild and rbuild, and apair adll\nblesl automabbile trudcks, motor\n.qetes and Motr veMl. of a ll .kinds\n:.,tb new. sa u-oadlheand) and al\nThe'tisrr p sad r wmiseories al gasso\nah e ahs of ais a nl nd\u007f ail thei\n:pats and aeesorsrs, to buy apd gel\nan oils, Sad anything else\nS\u007f used wdith or needed foi\ne, anaiaitaa .la dt, r tru rd\nPt'and tIlaxf0 I]\u007f;and r\"eoatruc\nafraan bsags *toW ilpate\naiwrt are apt hiresad\nst at is divided\nW san Fifty '(MG)\nofr a one uan\n*a erlob~i\nJoseph Winkler, of Arcadia, in e'\nBienville Parish, Louisiana. (1\nThe officers of this corporation shall 1\nbe a President and General Manager; p;\nVice-President; Secretary and Treas-\nurer and Assistant General Manager, f\ntogether with such other offices as\nthe board of directors may fom time 01\nto time see fit and proper to select.\nThe officers for the first year, or\nuntil their successors have been elect\ned and qualified shall be, R. E. Smith, o1\npresident and general manager; Jo d\nseph Winkler, vice-president; J. C.\nRoberts, secretary-treasurer and as\nsistant general manager.\nARICLE 3.\nThe first annual. meetsj of the n\nstockholders of this corporation shall\nbe held at Arcadia, at the offices of\nthe company, in Bienville Parish,\nLouisiana on the third Wednesday in P\nDecember, 1921, and annually there- s\nafter for the purpose of electing a\nboard of directors for the ensuing\nyear, and for the conduct of such c\nother business as may properly come g\nbefore the stockholders at such times. 11\nThe board of directors so chosen, I\nshall at once organize and elect from\namong their numpber a president and\ngeneral manager, a vice-president, and\na secretary-treasurer and assistant v\ngeneral manager. The board of dierc\ntors is vested with al 1 co'rporate\npowers ,subject to such restrictions as\nare contained in this charter, the con\nstitution and laws of the State of\nLouisiana, and the constitution and\nlaws of the United States of America.\nThe names and Post Office addresses\nof the subscribers to this charter, anm\na statement of the shares of stock\nwhich each agrees to take in the cor 4\nporation and a description and valua. I\ntion of the property if any, to be given\nin exchange for stock, as required by\nSection 3, of Act No. 267 of 1914, 1\nshown in a detailed and itemized state\nment annexed to and made a part\nhereof.\nIn testimony whereof the said\nparties have hereunto signed their\nnames in my office, in the presence ofl\nW. M. Deas and Chas. M. Roberts\ncompetent witnesses at Aracdia, in\nBlenville Parish, Louisiana on this\nthe 22nd day of, December,' in the\nyear of our Lord Nintesen Hnntred\nand Twenty (1920), after due read\ning of the whole.\nR. E. SMITH,\nJOS. WINKLER,\nJ. C. ROBERTS.\nATTEST:\nW. M. DEAS,\nCHAS. M. ROBERTS.\nS CARL GOFF, Notary Public\nState of.'Louisiana, Parish of Bien\nville.\nf W. L. Smelley, Dy. Clerk Distrlct\nCourt in aird for Bienville Parish, di\nhereby certify that the above and\nforegoing is a true and correct copy\nof the original as recorded in Book\nP\"A\" Page \"92\" Charter record in and\nfor Bienville Parish Louisiana.\nThis Pecember 22nd 1920.\nW. L. 8M LLEY. Dy. Clerk Dis\nthlct Court.\nSHERIFF'S SALE\nFirst National Bank Vs. B. A, Brewer.\nNo. 5448, Third Judiqial Court,\nState of Louisiana, Parish of Ble,\nSvllue.\nUnder and by vihtue of a writ of\nexecution issued out of the above nam\nI ed Honorable Court and to me direct.\ned, I have seized and will offer for\ni sale to the last and highest bidder for.\nScash, with benefit of appraisement, at\nSthe principle fr9nt door of the Court\ni house .in. Arcadia, Bieaville Parl\u007f)\nLa., within legal sale hours on\nSaFurday Fta vy Sib 1921\nthe following descrije4 property, to\nwil;\nOne Studebaker Automobile, 191f\nmodel, painted red, 1 resieldence mqd\nlot E 1-2 of Lot 1, Block 29, in Ar\n-eadia, Louisiana.\nS,The above deecribed propery to t\nisold as belbnging to the defendant, B\nr A. Brewer, and will be sold to satis\nfy matt writ of exeoeution and all cost.\nThla the 9th day of December, A.\nD., 1920.\nJ. E. CURRIE, Sheriff.\nSam D .i 1 vs. N. ai -Jap hw*,\nN. P,Third JI Dis\ntrles Court, BIandfli FUi, Is.\n,U der and by virte of a writ-os\nseizure and sale lased out of the\nabove named Honorable Court and to\nsme dIeCted~ I have se\u007fied and will\nobter for sale to the last and highest\nSbidder, for cash, at the principal front\ndoor of the oprt house in the town of\nAroadia, Bientille Parish, L9ulsuana,\n1hteaours on\n%S of tSWj S a osa%, e.i\n28; NW1.4 of NW1-, N1.2 of 19114\no i#E14, iee. 88 ly:ng wpet of tAr\nedig. and Liberty Bill road, all in\nai T*p. 17 N., R. 5W, containing 215\nI' sores more or less with all improve\n4 meqts thereon.\n.Said property seized as beloIg to\nila defe\u007fdantes, N L d \u007f10-d\nann, and will be sold-to asty (la,\nI- writ and all couts\nThio tk.e th day of Januar I.\n1.l 14\nS I, CUBBIE,\n-81hrl4 of Ble~avile Prhk la.\nIt it, ii-e.\ni\" eadtat..*etle b ,.i-\"\"t.\nndl that a ri.E bat, it a84\npeepry 4HsC~`DrH. WICI~irr\n~#~,tpmI~~b iggi~\nHOW YOU CAN HELP THE BLIND\nCHILD IN YOUR NEIGHBORHOOD\nHave you often pitied the blind child\nif your neighborhood and longed for\nt chane to help him?\nThe Louisiana State School for the\nBlind can help every blind boy and\ngirl in the State by supplyjng a good\neducation which will enable him to be\ncome a useful, self-respecting citizen.\ncapable of becoming partially or wholly\nself-supporting. The blind child why\nis allowed to grow up in ignorance\nand helplessness will sooner or later\nbecome a burden. on the parish i,\nwhich he lives. We all appreciate thal\nevery seeing child should have an edu\ncation in order to get on in the world:\n(let us not forget that the blind child\nis in even greater need of instruction\nfor hlie must fight the world's battles\nwith four senses instead of five. Ir\norder that no sightless child may bi\nneglected, we are asking citizens of the\nState to send the names and addresses\nof all blind acid partially blind chil\ndren to J. J. Murphy, Superintendent\nof the Louisiana state School for thi\nBlind, Baton Rouge, La.\nhis `school boards and instructs;\nmelntally sound blind children during\nterm of eight months each year. II\nmaintains primary and high school de\npartments, and, in additipn, gives n\nspecial courses in\" industrial work ami' t,\nmusic. Good food and daily, physical g\nculture are provided. The schools\ngrounds are extensive and afford splen V\ndid opportunities for outdoor life\nThere are no charges of any, kind, (fhe\nschool being supported entirely by the e\nState. The management of the school\nwill greatly appreciate any inforlia\ntion concerning any blind child who iU\nnot now receiving the advantages of\n:free education.\nJ. J. MURPHY,\n'Superintendent, Louisiana State Sehori\nfor thel Blind.\nCrim's 5, 10 and 25 Cent Store\nOld Time Prices back again. Ladles'\nHosiery 15 and 25e pair.\nMORTGAGE BLANKS AND NOTES\nChattel Mortgage Blanks, contain.\ning homestead waiver clause. Also\nMortgage Notes, Plain Notes and Con.\nI fesion otfJudgement Notes in pads.\nWe also have straight Mortgage\nblanks. We can' supply these in stock\nform, or print, them to order.\nBIENVILLI DIEMOCRAT,\nArcadia, Louisiana\nCONSTABIE SALE\nState of Louisiana, Parish of Bienville,\nIn Second Jqstlce Court, Ward 2,\nFirst National Bank of Gibsland Vs.\n(Clarence Chapman.\nUnder ahd by virtu$ of a Writ of\nFieri Ficias issued out of tle above\nnamed Hmaoral\u007f Court and to me di\nrected I have seized and will offer for\nsale to the last and highest bidder for\ni cash with the benefit of appraisement\nin the town of Gibsuand, Biepville\nI Parish, Louisiana, within legal salt\ng houis on\nSaturday, February'12, 192l\nI the following described property to\nwit:\nOne Ford automobile.\nThe above described property to be\nsold as belonging to the defendant,\nClarence Chapman, and will be sold t,\nsatisfy said writ of Execution and all\nc'ost.\nThis the 21st day of January, 1921\nP. C. BURNETTE,\nConstable, Ward Two.\n'f wUIsKEY CONSUMPTION DROPB\nOFF 64,M0,0 GALLONS IN 31(35.\nm~Washington, Jan. 23.-Whiskrdey coil\nIt sumptlon in the United States deereas\ned from 89,641,985 galons inl 1917 to\n5,581,553'gallons in 1920, the Orst year\nof prohibition under the constitutional\namendment, aceordln g to figures an\n,nouned today by the Anti-Saloon\nd League of America. 'Consumption of\nF.alcohol in the same years decreased\nfrom 71,081,121 gailoni to 22,89,355\nSgallot, the figures showed, while beer\nconsumption dropped\" from 60,177.819\nbarrels to 9,23'\u007f8O barrels.\nGraning that many minion gallons\nof alcohol and whiskey withdrawn for\nnon,beverage use have been diverted to\nbeverage use,\" said an accom