useholder. 'This was God\nhimself. (2) The vineyard. This\nmeans Israel (see Isa. 5:1-7; Jer. 2:21; ra\nPs. 80:8). The Lord went to particu- e\nlar pains to gather out this nation in\nand make it separate, bestowing pe- re\nculiar favors upon it. This vineyard I\nso well kept and provided for did not I\nbear fruit. (3) The husbandmen.\nThese were the spiritual guides, the w\nrulers and teachers of Israel, the mem- at\nbers of the sanhedrin. (4) The serv- ir\nsams. sent for the frlilts of the vine\nyard. These were the various proph\nets whom Cod sent to the nation. The\nmaltreatment and rejection 'of the\nprophets is fully set forth in the\nScriptures. They were beaten and\nkilled. (5) The SoM He is the Lord\nJesus Christ, God's only and beloved\nSon. He came into they midst.\nThey That Deny.\nThey that deny a God destroy man's\nnobility, for certainly man is of kin\nto the beasts by his body, and, if he\nbe not of kin to God by his spirit, he\nis a base and ignoble creature.\nBacon.\nThe Kingdom of God.\nThe kingdom of God Is not a husi\nness set up in rivalry with worldly\nbusiness, but a divine law regulating\nand a divine temper pervading the pur\nsuits of worldly business,-Doctor Mar\ntineau.\n.o-\nSAI.UMNI OF L. S. U'.\nTO ORGANIZE STATE I\nBf ton Rouge, Jan. 21.--W. B. Myei(k\nactive secretary and treasurer \"f ti2\nLouisiana State University, Alumni\ne Federation, will meet with the L \"S\nU. alumni of Lake Charles and sur\nromduling territory tomorrow, for the1\npurpose of organizibtthem into an ae.\ntive chapter of the federation. Th.\nmeeting will take place in the Majestic\nhotel, wbtire Colonel A. T. Prescott, a,'\nL. S. U., Griffin T Hawkins, Jr.. tem\nporary chairman of the Lake Charle:\nassociation, and W. P, Myrick will de\nliver addresses.\nSecretary Myrick will then proceed\nto DeRidder, where lie will organlza,\nBeauregard parish, January 25.--'1`i,\nLy Times. Shreveport.\nCzechoslovak Forests.\nA novel feature of Czchoslovak f4r\nest development is the principle that\nthe annual growth mpst equal or ex\nN eed the annul cut. This is a wise atld\nfarsighted policy. It is estimated that\n6,600,000 cubic meters of fire wood\nt and 9,400,000 cubic meters of commtr\ntel call timber are cut yearly. The'qugn\ntity used for fuel during and since toe\n0: war will be greatly reduced, In tie\n't very near future, through stimulated\nproduction of bituminous coal, ligntte\nand oil. At the' prevailing prices 4or\nSlumber competnt authorities estimate\nSthe value of the annual tlmber cut ito\nbe about $120,000,000.\nr Blind Piano FI er.,\nThe pianos of the schoolt of'Phi a\ndelphia iAre tuned and cared for bj a\nblind man whose time lq enti~ly\nt taken up by his visits to one sahol\n.building after another. He not osly\ne tunes the instruments, but he gdes\nSover the exterior and polishes the caj\nd apd ikeeps.them looking like new.\nMules Fr Sal!\n7 Plenty of Mules' of' ii\ngrades on hand.\nbSee me before buying\nS elsewhere\nJ. R. JORDA\nSArcadi, La.\nS.Get A Petical Education and A Good Position at\nPRACTICAL\nBUSINESS\nThe LARGEST and nost efficient Business. Training School in this section,\nestabhshed 21 years, ith graduates in almost every office in Shreveport and\nsection.\nGregg and Graham-Pittman Shorthand\nTouch Typewriting, raughon's ew C 3?y-righted Bo okkeeping and Higher\nAccounting, Burroughs Bookkeeping Machine, English, Office Practice, etc.\n'Positions secured. talogue and information on request Address\nI P. E. TOWNSLEY, Manager\nI... SHREVEPORT, LA.\nSaffror Once Royal Qolor.\nIn Ireland sntiron ea rly hecame a\nroyal volor and, for a long period af\nler such exclusiveness was taken away\nIn Erin, the yellow saffron-dyed shirt\nremained a mark of social distinction\nin the Hebrides. In art saffron was\nmuch employed in medieval il1ltmi\noated manuscrlpts, In combination\nwith tin foil as a substitute for gold,\nand, of course, at all periods the color.\ning of many textiles was done with\nlittle crocus stigmas.\nFor Sale or Trade!\n4000 acres for pasture, well fenced,\neverlasting spring water; 4 room\nhouse. Located 16 miles from Ros\nwell, New Mexico.\nC. IlOLSTUN \"MAND\nREPORT FURNISHED TO THE EXAMINER OF STATE\nBANKS BY THE\nThe First Trust &.Banking Co.\nARCAIDIA, LOUISIANA\nAT THE CLOSE OF BUSINESS DEC. 31st, 1920.\nL. 1. OOKE. Pres. .1. E. RIIEYNOIDS, Vice-Plres. W. M. DEAS, Cas r\n('IARL GOFF, Assistant Cashier\nRESOURCES\nDemand Loans 2,055.15\nLoans secured by mortgage............ 32,473.20\nOther loans and discounts 80,735.35\nI'nited States ionds 691.15\nBanking house, furniture and tixtures............................. 508.10\nOther real estate owned 1,600.00\nDui from. banks and bankers (other than above) ................$2,404.41\nChecks on other banks 6,152.52 8,556.93\nGold certificates .....................................................$1, 440.00\nSilver, nickel and copper coin......... 72.91\nNational bank notes and all issues U. S. Government\n(Except Gold certificate) 2,106.00 8,618.01\n\nCotton Insurance account 48.%\nTOTAL.................................................................. $1$,$ .39\nLIABILITIES\nCapital stock paid in....... 0,000.00.\nSurplus 2,000.00\nUndivided profits, less expenses and taxes paid....................................\nDividends unpaid 5,000.00\nIndividual deposits subject to check............... 28,770.29\nDemand-certificates of deposit '2,500.00 30,270.29\nIndividual savings deposits 23,0678.\nBills payable ,00 .0\nNotes and bills rediscounted 15,248.90\nState of Louisiana-Parish of Bienville.\nI, L. M. Tooke:,president, and I, Carl Goff, Ass't'Cahhler of thl bove\nnamed bank, do solemnly swear that the above statement is true to the best\nof my knowledge.and belief.\nL. M. TOOKE, President.\nCARL OFF, Assistant Cashier.\nSubscribed and sworn to before me, this the (th day of January, 1921\nBERTRA&, F. BARNETTE,\nNotary\nEVER BILIOUS?'\nCharleston, Miss.-Mrs. R. V. Heins, of this place,\nsiys: \"I have never had to use very much medicine,\nbecause if I felt headache, dizziness, or colds, bad taste\nSii the mouth, which comes from torpid liver, I would\ntake a dose or more of Black-Draught, and it would\nstraighten me out and make me feel as good as new.\nW have used in our family for years\nTHEDFORD'S\nand it certainly is the best liver medicine i ever saw.\nIt has not only saved me money, it has helped keep my\nsystem in shape, and has never' weakened me as so\nmany physics do. I recommend it to my friends and am\nglad to do so.\" Black-Draught is the old, reliable liver\nmedicine which you have doubtless heard much about\nWhen you feel badly all over, stomach not right, bad\ntaste in your mouth, bilious, or have a headache, try\nThedford's Black-Draught. At all Druggists.\nAlways lInsist on the Genuinel\n&I\n3reatest Man.\nLeonardo de Vihcl is considered by\nseveral competent judges to have th#\nstrongest clati to the title of the\ngreatest man in history. He was tdde\noutstldting g~lus in the golden 8;.,\nof gvcnlp, the :ge gf Shakespetre:\nILnuther. Frt+;slts. Cervantes. iflch e:\nI Angielo Titian aHni Raphuel.\nMuch in Little.\nThe brief style is that wh'4, ex.\npresses intch in tlttle.-Ben .Tla ona.","height":"31569","width":"18279"}}
